// Part 1 — Written explanation (add as a comment block):
// Explain:
// a) Why 'latest' makes it impossible to identify the code version
// b) Why rollback is unreliable with 'latest'
// c) How commit-SHA tagging solves both problems

// Part 2 — Show the expected 'docker images' output after three builds
// using commit SHA tags (simulate with example SHAs):
// Build 1: commit a1b2c3d
// Build 2: commit e4f5a6b
// Build 3: commit 7c8d9e0

tasks.solution:
// Part 1 — Explanation:
//
// a) 'latest' is a mutable tag — any new build overwrites it.
//    When the container crashes, running 'docker inspect <container>'
//    shows 'Image: myapp:latest', which tells you nothing about WHEN
//    the image was built or WHAT commit it contains.
//    With commit-SHA tags, 'docker inspect' shows 'myapp:e4f5a6b',
//    and 'git show e4f5a6b' shows exactly which lines of code are running.
//
// b) Rolling back with 'latest' means guessing. You would need to
//    find an older image — but if previous builds also pushed 'latest',
//    those images are gone from the tag. The only recovery is
//    rebuilding, which takes time and reintroduces the same broken code.
//    With commit-SHA tags, every past image sits in ECR under its own
//    immutable tag; rollback is 'docker pull myapp:a1b2c3d' — instant.
//
// c) Commit-SHA tagging creates a permanent, bidirectional index:
//    code commit ↔ image tag. Given any running container, you can
//    find the exact source. Given any commit, you can find the image
//    and any server running it.

// Part 2 — Expected state after three builds:

// docker images on Jenkins agent:
// REPOSITORY   TAG       IMAGE ID       CREATED
// myapp        a1b2c3d   img1abc...     3 hours ago
// myapp        e4f5a6b   img2def...     2 hours ago
// myapp        7c8d9e0   img3ghi...     1 hour ago

// ECR repository (3 images, each with its own immutable tag):
// Tag         Pushed
// a1b2c3d     3 hours ago
// e4f5a6b     2 hours ago
// 7c8d9e0     1 hour ago
//
// To roll back to Build 1:
// docker pull 123456789012.dkr.ecr.us-east-1.amazonaws.com/myapp:a1b2c3d
// docker run ... myapp:a1b2c3d
// No rebuild required. The image already exists in ECR.
